      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''Visas for Mexican Workers'' (editorial, Aug. 24), you qualify the ideas of Vicente Fox, Mexico's president-elect, regarding free labor movement across the open border as ''not practical anytime soon.''</p>
        <p>Such skepticism might derive from a resistance to recognize the contribution of Mexican immigrants to the United States economy. As a 1994 Department of Labor report concludes:</p>
        <p>''In effect, migrant workers, so necessary for the success of the labor-intensive U.S. agricultural system, subsidize that very system with their own and their families' indigence. The system functions to transfer costs to workers who are left with income so marginal that, for the most part, only newcomers and those with no other options are willing to work on our nation's farms.''</p>
        <p>If you were to give credence to these findings, Mr. Fox's ideas would not be as premature as you suggest.  JORGE A. BUSTAMANTE  Notre Dame, Ind., Aug. 24, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of sociology at the University of Notre Dame.</p>
      </block>
